1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
{The famous Milner-Barry Gambit.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3 a6 $1 {A great
little move that has really taken the sting out of White's pawn sacrifice. Its
main purpose is to prevent Nb5, while the a7 square might prove to be a useful
haven for the black queen or bishop in some variations.} 11. Qe2 Rc8 $5 {
Once again Atalik delays the development of his kingside. Usually Black
hurries to put his knight on c6 with Ne7 and Nc6, but the Turkish GM has
another route in mind for the horse.} 12. Kh1 {White breaks the pin on f2 so
that he can defend e5 with f2-f4.} Bc5 {Here we see a reason for Rc8- it
defends the bishop, so that 13.Be3 can be answered by 13...Qxe5 without
dropping a piece.} 13. f4 {this lets the knight go to h6 without being met by
Bxh6, breaking up Black's kingside. However, White was short of constructive
alternatives.} Nh6 $1 {The knight heads for the hole on e3.} 14. Bd2 Nf5 15.
Rad1 ({White is falling apart after} 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Rad1 Qc4 $1 17. Qf3 d4 {
etc.}) 15... Ne3 16. Bxe3 Qxe3 {Black has carried out his plan. He now has the
two bishops as well as an extra, protected passed pawn in the centre.
Nevertheless, he has to meet White's next move with care.} 17. Qg4 Bf8 $1 ({
After} 17... g6 $2 18. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 19. Rf3 {the black queen is suddenly
trapped!}) 18. Nxd5 $2 ({This attempt to blast open the e-file fails. Perhaps
he should have tried his luck with} 18. Rf3 Qb6 19. f5 $1 {even though Black
has} Qxb2) 18... exd5 19. e6 Bxe6 20. f5 h5 $1 {The white queen has no good
square, as if 21.Qh4 Be7 etc.} ({Of course not} 20... Bd7 $2 21. Rfe1) 21. Qa4+
Bd7 22. Qh4 Be7 23. f6 Bxf6 24. Qb4 Qe7 ({It's all over, for if} 24... Qe7 25.
Rfe1 Be6 {etc.}) 0-1

