1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 {The natural square for
the bishop, though after Black's reply White is more or less committed to
sacrificing his d pawn. That is why many players prefer} (6. Be2) 6... cxd4 7.
cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O {The famous Milner-Barry Gambit.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 ({Other ideas
include} 9. Nbd2 {which Joszef Nun has used to beat several GMs and}) (9. Ng5
$5) 9... Qxd4 10. Nc3 a6 $1 {A far sighted move. Black rules out Nb5 and
clears the a7 square for the dark squared bishop. Instead} (10... Qxe5 {
is the move popularised by John Watson.}) 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. Kh1 {White prepares
to defend e5 with f2-f4 before Black plays Ne7 and Nc6.} Nc6 13. f4 Bc5 {
The alternative is} (13... Nb4 {immediately.}) 14. Bd2 ({Or} 14. a3 Ba7 15. Bd2
g6 $1 ({Instead} 15... Qb6 16. b4 Qd8 17. Qh5 $1 Ne7 18. Rae1 g6 19. Qh6 {
gave White some attacking chances in Stets-Kuzmin, Alushta 1999.}) 16. b4 b5 $1
17. Bxb5 $6 {This is enterprising but Black can withstand the attack.} axb5 18.
Nxb5 Qb6 19. Nd6+ Kf8 20. f5 exf5 21. Bh6+ Kg8 22. Bg5 Bb8 $1 23. Bf6 Nxe5 $1
24. Bxe5 Bxd6 25. Bf6 h5 {and Black was winning in German-Rodriguez, Buenos
Aires 1996.}) 14... Nb4 15. Bb1 Ba7 $1 {Black makes way for the queen to
retreat to b6.} 16. a3 Nc6 17. Bd3 (17. b4 Qb6 ({Perhaps} 17... b5 $5 {as in
the Rodriguez game of the last note.}) 18. Bd3 (18. Qh5 $5) 18... g6 19. Rae1
h5 20. Nxd5 {Again an all out attack by White, but he eventually runs out of
pieces:} exd5 21. e6 Bxe6 22. f5 gxf5 23. Bg5 Kd7 24. Rxf5 Rae8 25. Rxf7+ Kc8
$1 26. Bf4 Bd7 $1 27. Bf5 Bxf5 28. Qxe8+ Rxe8 29. Rxe8+ Nd8 {and White
resigned in Stets-Burlai, Sevastopol 2000.}) 17... g6 $1 {An important move
which rules out f4-f5 except as a sacrifice and also prevents Qh5. It is
necessary as the black queen is going to vacate d4 and so won't be able to
answer Qh5? with Qxd3 or f4-f5 with Qxe5.} 18. Rac1 Qb6 19. b4 Nd4 $1 {Black
finds a way to strengthen further his grip on the centre dark squares. On f5
the knight will be ready to jump into e3.} 20. Qd1 Nf5 21. Na4 Qd8 22. Nc5 Bc6
23. Nxa6 Ne3 24. Bxe3 Bxe3 25. Rc2 O-O {Now it's clear the opening has been a
disaster for White. Black has a dominant dark squared bishop, a perfectly safe
king and nasty tactical threats on the a file. The pressure soon restores the
pawn advantage and despite White's stubborn resistance the end is inevitable.}
26. Qa1 Ba4 27. Re2 Qb6 28. Nc5 Bxc5 29. bxc5 Qxc5 30. Rc1 Qe7 31. Rc3 Bc6 32.
Qc1 d4 33. Rb3 Bd5 34. Rb4 Rfc8 35. Qg1 Rc3 36. Rxd4 Qxa3 37. Be4 Rc1 38. Re1
Rxe1 39. Qxe1 Bxe4 40. Rxe4 Qd3 41. h3 Ra1 42. Qxa1 Qxe4 43. Qf1 h5 44. h4 b5
45. Kh2 b4 46. Qf2 b3 47. Qd2 Kg7 48. Kg3 Qc2 49. Qd8 b2 50. Qf6+ Kg8 51. Qd8+
Kh7 52. Qe7 Qf5 0-1

