1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 {There isn't too much theory on 9.Nbd2. Therefore analysis
to this game is entirely my own, with the help of Fritz. So please don't take
anything on trust, especially in the sharp lines given after 9... Bc5- watch
out for mistakes!} 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Qb6 8. O-O
Nxd4 9. Nbd2 $5 {Certainly this is worth a try, as the mainline Milner-Barry
with 9.Nxd4 etc. is looking grim for White.} Bc5 $1 {The crucial test of
White's ninth move. Other continuations seem to grant White easy compensation
for his pawn, for example} (9... Nc6 10. Nb3 Qc7 $6 {Better to wait to see if
the queen is attacked with Be3 before playing this retreat.} 11. Bf4 Nge7 12.
Bg3 g6 $6 13. Bf4 Bg7 14. Rc1 h6 15. Re1 a6 16. h4 $1 {and White had a bind on
both sides of the board in Smerdon, D-Vaidya, C/Kochin IND 2004.}) (9... Nxf3+
10. Nxf3 Rc8 11. Ng5 $1 Nh6 12. Nxh7 {The manoeuvre Ng5 and Nxh7 might seem
somewhat odd, but it is a fundamental idea for White in this line. Besides
grabbing a pawn back, it also stops Black castling kingside and introduces the
idea of Bxh6, winning the f6 square for the white knight.} Bb5 13. Bxh6 gxh6
14. Bxb5+ Qxb5 15. Rc1 Bc5 16. Nf6+ Ke7 17. Qf3 Rc6 {and White had attacking
chances which he increased by opening lines with} 18. b4 Bb6 19. Ne4 $1 Rh7 ({
If} 19... dxe4 20. Qf6+ {wins the rook}) 20. Nd6 Qxb4 21. Nxb7 Rxc1 22. Rxc1
Qb2 23. Re1 {and White went onto win in Smerdon, D-West, G/Melbourne AUS 2004.}
) 10. b4 $5 {If this natural looking attempt to open lines fails, then I
believe White must be in trouble. Nothing else is as forceful e.g.} (10. Nxd4
Bxd4 11. Nf3 Ne7 {and Black looks secure.}) 10... Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 Qxb4 12. Ng5 (
{Perhaps White should investigate} 12. Rb1 Qa4 ({or} 12... Qa5 13. Ng5) 13. Bc2
Qxa2 14. Rxb7) 12... Qa4 13. Qh5 $2 {An obvious attacking move but in what
follows the queen becomes vulnerable to exchange by Nh6 and Qg4!- the last
thing White wants to happen. No better is} (13. Qf3 $2 Nh6 14. Nxh7 Qg4 {
and there go the queens again- but interesting was}) (13. Bc2 $5 Qc6 $5 {
Getting the queen back to safety seems the best approach, though in fact she
might end up a target here for a future Rc1.} (13... Qd4 14. Qf3 $1 Nh6 {
and now} ({not} 14... Qxa1 $2 15. Qxf7+ Kd8 16. Qxg7 {when h8 goes with a
rampant attack for White.}) 15. Bf4 $1 {gives White enough play for the pawn,
while fantasists might like to try out} (15. Be3 $6 Qxe5 16. Bxc5 Qxg5 {
when the dark squares around the black king are loose, but it will take
something major for White to break through the light square barrier.})) (13...
Qh4 14. g3 $1 Qd4 15. Qf3 Nh6 {and we have the 13... Qd4 line but with g2-g3
added. The same comments as above apply to} 16. Bf4 $5 {and} (16. Be3 $6 Qxe5
17. Bxc5 Qxg5)) 14. Nxh7 ({White runs into trouble after} 14. Qh5 Nh6 15. Nxh7
Bd4 $1 16. Bxh6 Qxc2 {but you might want to delve deeper into other moves
after 14.Qh5.}) 14... O-O-O ({or} 14... Ne7 15. Bg5 $5) 15. Bg5 {intending Rc1
etc. and despite the weird knight on h7 White has definite play for the pawn.})
13... Nh6 14. Nxh7 Rxh7 $5 {This leads to a highly promising endgame, but the
greedy} (14... Qd4 $1 {attacking both d3 and a1 looks very strong e.g.} 15. Qe2
({or} 15. Bxh6 Qxd3 {and Black wins a piece on the h-file.}) 15... Nf5 $1) 15.
Bxh7 Qg4 $1 {Pouring cold water on White's attacking aspirations.} 16. Qh3 ({Or
} 16. Qxg4 Nxg4 {when besides the threat of taking on e5 or blocking in the
bishop with 17...g6, White has to reckon with 17...Bb5. Still, perhaps} 17. Bd3
Nxe5 18. Be2 {would have been the best way to fight on, though Black
undoubtedly has the better of it due to his protected passed pawn.}) 16... Qxh3
17. gxh3 Bc6 {Nominally speaking, White is ahead on material, but his pawn
structure is riddled with holes and his rooks have no open lines: the black
pawns and pieces form a barrier that stretches across the whole board.} 18. Rb1
Kd7 19. Rb3 Rh8 20. Bd3 Nf5 21. Bxf5 exf5 22. Kg2 Ke6 {An excellent post for
the black king.} 23. Rg3 d4+ 24. Kg1 g6 25. Ba3 Bb6 $1 {Declining the exchange
of bishops ensures that the white rooks are held at bay.} 26. Bd6 Rh4 {Now
Black prepares the decisive advance of the passed pawn.} 27. Rd1 Re4 28. Kf1
Bb5+ 29. Kg2 Be2 30. Rd2 Ba5 31. Rxe2 Rxe2 32. Bc5 Bc3 33. a3 a5 34. Kf3 Re1
0-1

